    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA323-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu tōḻi iravukkuṟi nērntatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante granted a night tryst.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA323">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            ōṅkit tōṉṟun tīṅkaṭ peṇṇai</l>
<l>            naṭuva ṇatuvē teyya maṭavara</l>
<l>            lāyamum yāṉu maṟiyā tavaṇa</l>
<l>            māya naṭpiṉ māṇala moḻintuniṉ</l>
<l>            kiḷaimai koṇṭa vaḷaiyār muṉkai</l>
<l>            nallō ṭantai ciṟukuṭip pākkam</l>
<l>            pulivari yekkarp puṉṉai yutirtta</l>
<l>            malitā tūtun tēṉō ṭoṉṟi</l>
<l>            vaṇṭimi riṉṉicai kaṟaṅkat tiṇṭērt</l>
<l>            terimaṇi kēṭṭalu maritē</l>
<l>            varumā ṟītavaṇ maṟavā tīmē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>It is in the middle<note place="foot">Here I do not see a way to render in the translation the admonishing nuance of the particle <term xml:lang="ta">teyya</term>.</note></l>
<l>of palmyra trees with sweet toddy that appear high,</l>
<l>the village<note place="foot">Here we have to assume that <term xml:lang="ta">pākkam</term> is the subject of <term xml:lang="ta">naṭuvaṇatē-teyya</term>, in spite of the missing particle marking. It might be possible to argue that it is meant as an open-ended postposition, since it is also from the village where it is difficult to hear the chariot’s bell of the following sentence.</note> with small homes of the father of the good one</l>
<l>with forearms full of bangles who has taken up a relationship with you,</l>
<l>[her] glorious innocence staying behind in the deceptive intimacy</l>
<l>[and] us there, the companions and I not knowing in [our] simplicity.</l>
<l>It will be difficult to hear at all the clear bell</l>
<l>of the firm chariot, while the humming sweet sounds of the bees sound,</l>
<l>becoming one with the honey<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">tēṉōṭu oṉṟi</term> is read by tradition as a reference to a second kind of bee, but is it not more likely that it simply is a way of expressing that the bees are deeply engaged in their business of making honey?</note>, filling themselves on the rich pollen</l>
<l>dropped by the Puṉṉai trees in the tiger-lined dunes.</l>
<l>This [is] the way to come there. Don’t forget.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
